<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection> xml:id="subsec-does-srs-matter" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>How Much Does It Matter If You Do Not Have a Simple Random Sample?</title>
    <p>
        In practice, many datasets are not obtained through simple random sampling. Does this mean that statistical analysis is 
        invalid? Not necessarily. The impact depends on how the sample was selected and whether the sampling method introduces bias 
        that affects the conclusions of the study.
    </p>
    <p>
        Some departures from simple random sampling are intentional and can be accounted for during the analysis. For example, 
        in <term><em>stratified sampling</em></term>, the population is divided into meaningful groups before sampling. 
        Although this creates a structured sampling design rather than a purely random one, it often improves the precision of 
        statistical estimates. Appropriate statistical methods can then be used to account for the sampling design.
    </p>
    <p>
        More generally, the purpose of random sampling is to obtain a sample that is representative of the population of interest. 
        A sample that is not perfectly random may still provide reliable conclusions if the characteristics that influence the study 
        are well represented. Conversely, even a large sample can produce misleading results if important groups are systematically 
        excluded or overrepresented.
    </p>
    <p>
        When designing a study, researchers should carefully define the target population and select a sampling method that is 
        appropriate for that population. Practical considerations such as time, cost, and accessibility often make convenience 
        sampling unavoidable. In such cases, it is important to recognise the limitations of the sample and consider how these limitations 
        might affect the interpretation of the results.
    </p>
    <p>
        Similarly, when evaluating the results of a study, it is not sufficient to simply note that the sample was not randomly selected. 
        Instead, the important question is whether the sampling method is likely to have introduced bias that affects the validity 
        or generalisability of the conclusions. A thoughtful assessment of the sampling process provides a much stronger basis for 
        evaluating statistical evidence than simply identifying that a convenience sample was used.
    </p>
</subsection>